To get detailed information about your health care coverage, please see your Evidence of Coverage (EOC). The network providers listed in this directory have agreed to provide you with your health care services. You may go to any of our network providers listed in this directory. If you have been going to one network provider, you are not required to continue to go to that same provider. In some cases, you may get covered services from out-of-network providers. Out-of-network providers are under no obligation to treat HealthPartners Journey enrollees, except in emergencies. For a decision about whether we will cover an out-of-network service, we encourage you or your provider to ask us for a pre-service organization determination before you receive the service. Please call our Member Services Department at 952-883-6655 or 866-233-8734, Oct. 1 through March 31, we take calls from 8 a.m. to 8 p.m. CT, seven days a week. From April 1 to Sept. 30, call us 8 a.m. to 8 p.m. CT Monday through Friday to speak with a representative. On Saturdays, Sundays and Federal holidays, you can leave a message and we'll get back to you within one business day. TTY users should call 711. You may also refer to your Evidence of Coverage (EOC) for more information, including the cost sharing that applies to out-of-network services.You can choose to receive care from out-of-network providers. Our plan will cover services from either in-network or out-of-network providers, as long as the services are covered benefits and are medically necessary. However, if you use out-of-network providers, your share of the costs for your covered services may be higher. In most cases, if you get care from an out-of-network provider, that provider must be eligible to participate in Medicare. Except for emergency care, we cannot pay a provider who is not eligible to participate in Medicare. If you receive care from a provider who is not eligible to participate in Medicare, you will be responsible for the full cost of the services you receive. Check with your provider before receiving services to confirm that they are eligible to participate in Medicare. You don't need to get a referral or prior authorization when you get care from out-of-network providers. However, before getting services from out-of-network providers you may want to ask for a pre-visit coverage decision to confirm that the services you are getting are covered and are medically necessary. If an out-of-network provider asks you to pay for covered services, please contact Member Services. To submit claims, you should mail them to: HealthPartners Claims Dept. 8170 33rd Ave. S. P.O. Box 1289 Minneapolis, MN 55440-1289 Section I - Introduction5You should never pay any out-of-network provider more than what the plan is allowed by Medicare. The provider has a right to get his/her fees, but doesn't have a right to get them from you. If an out-of-network provider sends you a bill that you think we should pay, please contact Member Services. Generally, it is best to ask an out-of-network provider to bill Original Medicare first, and then to bill us for the remaining amount. We may require the out-of-network provider to bill Original Medicare. We will then pay any applicable Medicare coinsurance and deductibles minus your copayments on your behalf. You may get covered emergency medical care whenever you need it, anywhere in the United States or its territories. Emergency care can always be obtained in or out of the service area from the nearest available provider. You also may get covered emergency medical care whenever you need it, outside the United States, anywhere in the world. When you are outside the service area and cannot get care from a network provider, you can access emergency and urgently needed services from any provider. You must use plan providers except in emergency situations. Emergency care can always be obtained in or out of the service area from the nearest available provider. When in the service area you must use plan providers for urgent care. When out of the service area urgent care may be obtained from the first available provider. In addition, when out of the service area you can obtain dialysis treatment from any qualified dialysis provider. With the exception of emergencies or urgent care, it may cost more to get care from out-of-network providers.What is the service area for HealthPartners Journey? the CareLineSM service? After regular clinic hours, call our CareLine service to talk directly with skilled nurses who are specially trained to help you over the phone. A CareLine nurse might suggest home care, a visit to your clinic the next day, a trip to an urgent care clinic, or a visit to an emergency room. Whatever your health care needs or questions, CareLine nurses will give you guidance based on the condition you describe and, if necessary, direct you to the facility that is most appropriate for your situation. They'll even contact the urgent care center so they're prepared to meet your needs when you arrive. What urgent care centers are available? The urgent care centers listed on the following pages are available to all HealthPartners UnityPoint Health members — just walk in. In addition, some clinics offer urgent care on site (see clinic listings). The urgent care centers affiliated with your regular clinic will most likely be able to get access to your medical records and more easily coordinate any needed follow up care. HealthPartners Journey contracts with 50 facilities of this type. Providers are organized first by state, city, then alphabetically by facility name.
